Climate is over a long period of time; composite of weather.

Weather and Climate

• Seasons are not very pronounced.
• Relatively dry form November to April
• Wet during the rest of the year
• Climate of Cebu City
• Type 4
• Rainfall is evenly distributed throughout the year
• General Santos
Season
• Season: is a division of the year based on changes in weather, ecology,
and the number of daylight hours in a given region.
• Climate of the Philippines is divided into 2 main seasons:
• Rainy season, from June to early October.
• Dry season, from latter part of October to May.
• The causes seasons.
• Tilt of the Earth's axis
• Position of the Earth in relation to the Sun.
Relationship of Sun Angle and Solar Radiation
• The sun angle influences the intensity of solar radiation of the Earth's
surface.
Solstices and Equinoxes
Atmosphere
• Atmosphere is the envelope of gas surrounding the Earth
• The atmosphere is composed of difference gases.
Components of the Atmosphere
• Nitrogen - 78.084%
• Oxygen - 20.946%
• Argon - 0.934%
• Carbon Dioxide - 0.0397% or 397 ppm
• Neon - 18.2 ppm
• Helium - 5.24 ppm
• Methane - 1.5 ppm
• Krypton - 1.14 ppm
• Hydrogen - 0.5 ppm
Variable Components of Air
• Water Vapor
• Up to 4% of the air's volume.
• Forms cloud and precipitation.
• Absorbs heat energy from the Earth.
• Aerosols
• Tiny solid and liquid particles.
• Water vapor can condense on solids.
• Reflect Sunlight.
• Help color sunrise and sunset.
Variable Components of Air
• Ozone
• Three atoms of oxygen (O3).
• Distribution not uniform.
• Concentrated between 10 to 50 kilometers above the surface.
• Absorbs harmful UV radiation.
• Human activity is depleting ozone by adding chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs).
Vertical Structure of the Atmosphere
• Thermosphere
• No well-defined upper limit.
• Fraction of atmosphere's mass.
• Gases moving at high speeds.
• Mesosphere
• About 50 km to 80 km.
• Temperature decreases.
• Outer boundary is named the Mesopause.
Vertical Structure of the Atmosphere
• Stratosphere
• About 12 km to 15 km.
• Temperature increases at the top.
• Another boundary is named the Stratopause.
• Troposphere
• Temperature decreases with altitude.
• Thickness varies - average height is 12 km.
• Outer boundary is named the Tropopause.
Pressure Changes
• Pressure is the weight of the air above.
• Average sea level pressure is slightly more than 1000 millibars.
• Pressure decreases with altitude.
Atmospheric Heating
• Heat is always transferred from warmer to cooler objects.
Radiation
• Electromagnetic Radiation is governed by basic laws:
• All objects, at whatever temperature, emit radiation.
• Hotter objects radiate more total energy per unit than cooler objects do.
• The hotter the radiating body, the shorter the wavelegngth of maximum
radiation.
• Objects that are good absorbed of radiation are good emitters as well.
• The Electromagnetic Spectrum
• Composed of:
• Gamma rays
• X rays
• Ultraviolet
• Visible light
• Violet
• Blue
• Green
• Yellow
• Infrared
• Microwaves
• Radio waves
• FM radio

• AM radio
• Long radio waves
Radiation
Radiation
• Average Distribution of Incoming Solar Radiation.
• Atmosphere is largely transparent to incoming solar radiation.
• Atmospheric effects:
• Reflection – Albedo
• Scattering
• Absorption
• Heating of the atmosphere is termed the Greenhouse Effect
• Greenhouse Gases:
• Carbon Dioxide
• Water Vapor
• Methane
